{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":20776,"name":"","username":"nergal","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/n/7c8e57/{size}.png","created_at":"2017-09-15T14:25:55.271Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThis is a pretty basic 3D question I guess. But I have objects that rotate since they are rigid-bodies and when I raycast towards them I want to create new objects relative to their rotations.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMore specific; It’s a voxel-object that I want to explode and all debris should be created relative to the objects rotation. Otherwise they are placed in the same structure as the object in it’s non-rotated state.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eExample:\u003cbr\u003e\nVector3 body_pos = body-\u0026gt;GetPosition();\u003cbr\u003e\nQuaternion body_rot = body-\u0026gt;GetRotation();\u003cbr\u003e\nint voxel_pos_x = X;\u003cbr\u003e\nint voxel_pos_y = Y;\u003cbr\u003e\nint voxel_pos_z = Z;\u003cbr\u003e\nVector3 new_relative_pos = body_rot * Vector3(body_pos.x_+voxel_pos_x, body_pos.y_+voxel_pos_y, body_pos.z_+voxel_pos_x);\u003cbr\u003e\nCreateMyNewObject(new_relative_pos);\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBut this calculation seems way wrong. Hints please? \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=5\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-09-15T14:25:55.271Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":34,"readers_count":33,"score":21.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":3568,"topic_slug":"position-with-rotation-in-mind","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":825,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"